The data is loaded in and any rows with missing data are dropped. I decided to keep remove the county variable despite poverty rates being highly regional and the county would be valuable in informing a prediction. There are two main reasons for getting rid of it, neither of which I thought outweight the value gained by keeping it. The first is that the number of counties is very high and some of them have few observations and this may lead to the model overfitting. The second is that, beacuse of the number of unique counties, once they are one hot encoded they add a signifigant number of columns to the data set and would slows down fitting signifigantly.

plt.show()

Quantiles:     [6.2, 16.3, 31.6]
Expert Ranges: [10.5, 21.1, 30.55]

Here the target feature is split into 4 classes. I started by looking at where the bounds would lie if the an even distribution was put in each class. Next, I did some research on child poverty rates and goals that are being set in the United States. The goal that was most commonly mentioned was to reduce child poverty by 50%. I used this to inform the bounds of the classes. The first divide was the mean value (21.1) which sections the data into two classes where one in higher than average and one is lower than average. This way half of the classes are for places where child poverty is better than the national average and half are for worse. The next boundry was placed at the goal child poverty rate of 10.5%. The last boundry was mirrord at 50% above the average to split between worse than average and in danger. The left each class with the following ranges:

Class 0: 0 - 10.5 Already at the goal rate or better

Class 1: 10.5 - 21.1 Better than average but not at the goal rate

Class 2: 21.1 - 31.7 Worse than average but not extreme

Class 3: 31.7 - 100 Very high child poverty rate

This splits the data into 4 distinct classes where each one may require a diiferent amount of attention to bring the overall child poverty rate down to the goal rate. These classes are not quite evenly distributed, but they are close enough that it can be accounted for using SMOTE.

class MultiLayerPerceptron(object):
    def __init__(self, layers=2, n_hidden=30, C=0.0, epochs=500, eta=0.001, random_state=None, save_grad=False, 
                decrease_const=0.0, shuffle=True, minibatches=1, momentum=None, gamma=0.0):
        xp.random.seed(random_state)
        self.layers = layers
        self.n_hidden = n_hidden
        self.l2_C = C
        self.epochs = epochs
        self.eta = eta
        self.save_grad = save_grad
        self.decrease_const = decrease_const
        self.shuffle = shuffle
        self.minibatches = minibatches
        self.momentum = momentum
        self.gamma = gamma
        self.epsilon = 1e-8
        
    @staticmethod
    def _encode_labels(y):
        """Encode labels into one-hot representation"""
        
        if USE_GPU:
            onehot = cp.asarray(pd.get_dummies(y.get()).values.T)
        else:
            onehot = pd.get_dummies(y).values.T
            
        return onehot

    def _initialize_weights(self):
        """Initialize weights Glorot and He normalization."""
        W = []
        b = []

        # create weights for input layer x hidden layer
        init_bound = 4*xp.sqrt(6.0 / (self.n_hidden[0] + self.n_features_ + 1))
        W.append(xp.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound, (self.n_hidden[0], self.n_features_)))
        b.append(xp.zeros((self.n_hidden[0], 1)))

        # create weights for all hidden layer x hidden layer
        for i in range(0, self.layers - 2):
            init_bound = 4*xp.sqrt(6.0 / (self.n_hidden[i] + self.n_hidden[i+1] + 1))
            W.append(xp.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound, (self.n_hidden[i], self.n_hidden[i + 1])))
            b.append(xp.zeros((self.n_hidden[i + 1], 1)))

        # create weights for hidden layer x output layer
        init_bound = 4*xp.sqrt(6.0 / (self.n_hidden[-1] + self.n_output_ + 1))
        W.append(xp.random.uniform(-init_bound, init_bound, (self.n_output_, self.n_hidden[-1])))
        b.append(xp.zeros((self.n_output_, 1)))
            
        return W, b
    
    @staticmethod
    def _sigmoid(z):
        """Use scipy.special.expit to avoid overflow"""
        # 1.0 / (1.0 + np.exp(-z))
        return expit(z)
    
    @staticmethod
    def _L2_reg(lambda_, W):
        """Compute L2-regularization cost"""
        # only compute for non-bias terms
        L2s = 0.0
        for w in W:
            L2s += xp.mean(w ** 2)

        return (lambda_) * xp.sqrt(L2s)
    
    def _cost(self, output, Y_enc, W):
        """Get the objective function value"""
        cost = -xp.mean(xp.nan_to_num((Y_enc*xp.log(output)+(1-Y_enc)*xp.log(1-output))))
        L2_term = self._L2_reg(self.l2_C, W)
        return cost + L2_term
    
    def _feedforward(self, X, W, b):
        """Compute feedforward step"""
        A = []
        Z = []

        A.append(X.T)
        Z.append(W[0] @ A[0] + b[0])

        for i in range(1, self.layers):
            A.append(self._sigmoid(Z[i - 1]))
            Z.append(W[i] @ A[i] + b[i])

        A.append(self._sigmoid(Z[-1]))

        return A, Z

    def _get_gradient(self, A, Z, Y_enc, W):
        """Compute gradient step using backpropagation."""

        V = [None] * self.layers
        V[-1] = (A[-1] - Y_enc)

        # V1 = A2*(1-A2)*(W2.T @ V2)
        for i in range(self.layers - 1, 0, -1):
            V[i - 1] = A[i] * (1 - A[i]) * (W[i].T @ V[i])

        grad = [None] * self.layers
        gradb = [None] * self.layers

        for i in range(0, self.layers):
            grad[i] = V[i] @ A[i].T
            gradb[i] = xp.sum(V[i], axis=1).reshape((-1,1))

        return grad, gradb
    
    def predict(self, X):
        """Predict class labels"""
        A, _ = self._feedforward(X, self.W, self.b)
        y_pred = xp.argmax(A[-1], axis=0)
        return y_pred
    
    
    def fit(self, X, y, print_progress=False, XY_test=None):
        """ Learn weights from training data. With mini-batch"""
        if USE_GPU:
            X = cp.asarray(X)
            y = cp.asarray(y)

        X_data, y_data = X.copy(), y.copy()
        Y_enc = self._encode_labels(y)
        
        # init weights and setup matrices
        self.n_features_ = X_data.shape[1]
        self.n_output_ = Y_enc.shape[0]
        self.W, self.b = self._initialize_weights()

        if self.save_grad:
            self.grad_ = [xp.zeros(self.epochs) for _ in range(self.layers)]

        if self.momentum == "RMSprop":
            V_prev = [xp.zeros(w.shape) for w in self.W]
            Vb_prev = [xp.zeros(b.shape) for b in self.b]

        self.cost_ = []
        self.score_ = []
        # get starting acc
        self.score_.append(xp.mean(self.predict(X_data) == y_data))
        
        # keep track of validation, if given
        if XY_test is not None:
            X_test = XY_test[0].copy()
            y_test = XY_test[1].copy()
            self.val_score_ = []
            self.val_score_.append(xp.mean(self.predict(X_test) == y_test))
            
        for i in range(self.epochs):

            # adaptive learning rate
            eta = self.eta / (1 + self.decrease_const*i)
            eta = max(eta, self.eta / 1000)

            if print_progress>0 and (i+1) % print_progress==0:
                print('Epoch: %d/%d' % (i+1, self.epochs), end='\r')

            if self.shuffle:
                idx_shuffle = xp.random.permutation(y_data.shape[0])
                X_data, Y_enc, y_data = X_data[idx_shuffle], Y_enc[:, idx_shuffle], y_data[idx_shuffle]

            mini = np.array_split(xp.arange(y_data.shape[0]), self.minibatches)
            mini_cost = []
            for idx in mini:

                # feedforward
                A, Z = self._feedforward(X_data[idx], self.W, self.b)
                
                cost = self._cost(A[-1], Y_enc[:, idx], self.W)
                mini_cost.append(cost) # this appends cost of mini-batch only

                # compute gradient via backpropagation
                grad, gradb = self._get_gradient(A, Z, Y_enc[:, idx], self.W)

                if self.save_grad:
                    for j in range(self.layers):
                        self.grad_[j][i] += xp.mean(grad[j])

                if self.momentum == "RMSprop":
                    # RMSprop for weights
                    G = [w ** 2 for w in grad]
                    V = [self.gamma * v + (1 - self.gamma) * g for v, g in zip(V_prev, G)]
                    V_prev = V
                    rho = [1 / xp.sqrt(v + self.epsilon) * w for v, w in zip(V, grad)]

                    # RMSprop for bias
                    Gb = [w ** 2 for w in gradb]
                    Vb = [self.gamma * v + (1 - self.gamma) * g for v, g in zip(Vb_prev, Gb)]
                    Vb_prev = Vb
                    rhob = [1 / xp.sqrt(v + self.epsilon) * w for v, w in zip(Vb, gradb)]

                    # update weights
                    for i in range(self.layers - 1):
                        self.W[i] -= eta * rho[i]
                        self.b[i] -= eta * rhob[i]

                else:
                    # update weights
                    for i in range(self.layers - 1):
                        self.W[i] -= eta * grad[i]
                        self.b[i] -= eta * gradb[i]
                
            if self.save_grad:
                for j in range(self.layers):
                    self.grad_[j][i] = self.grad_[j][i] / self.minibatches

            self.cost_.append(mini_cost)
            self.score_.append(xp.mean(self.predict(X_data) == y_data))
            if XY_test is not None:
                self.val_score_.append(xp.mean(self.predict(X_test) == y_test))
                
            
        return self

This is the neural network that will be used in the rest of the lab

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

plt.style.use('ggplot')

def print_result(nn,X_train,y_train,X_test,y_test,title="",color="red"):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize=(30,10))

    gs = fig.add_gridspec(1, 2)
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, 0])
    ax2 = fig.add_subplot(gs[0, 1])
    
    print("=================")
    print(title,":")
    yhat = nn.predict(X_train)
    print('Resubstitution acc:',accuracy_score(y_train,yhat))
    
    yhat = nn.predict(X_test)
    print('Validation acc:',accuracy_score(y_test,yhat))
    
    if hasattr(nn,'val_score_'):
        ax1.plot(range(len(nn.val_score_)), nn.val_score_, color=color,label=title)
        ax1.set_ylabel('Validation Accuracy')

    else:
        ax1.plot(range(len(nn.score_)), nn.score_, color=color,label=title)
        ax1.set_ylabel('Resub Accuracy')
        
    ax1.set_title('Accuracy')
    ax1.set_xlabel('Epochs')
    ax1.legend(loc='best')
    ax1.grid(True)

    cost_avgs = [np.mean(x) for x in nn.cost_]

    ax2.plot(range(len(cost_avgs)), cost_avgs, color='red')
    ax2.set_title('Cost over epochs')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Cost')
    ax2.set_xlabel('Epochs')
    ax2.grid(True)

    # set font size
    for item in ([ax1.title, ax1.xaxis.label, ax1.yaxis.label] + ax1.get_xticklabels() + ax1.get_yticklabels()):
        item.set_fontsize(20)
    
    for item in ([ax2.title, ax2.xaxis.label, ax2.yaxis.label] + ax2.get_xticklabels() + ax2.get_yticklabels()):
        item.set_fontsize(20)

    # make the legend bigger
    ax1.legend(prop={'size': 20})

This function prints both accuracy and the cost over time for the model

In [ ]:
def print_gradient_magnitudes(nn):
    if hasattr(nn,'grad_') != True:
        return

    for i in range(nn.layers):
        # plot absolute value of gradient
        plt.plot(abs(nn.grad_[i]), label="Layer " + str(i + 1))

    plt.legend()
    plt.ylabel('Average gradient magnitude')
    plt.xlabel('Epochs')
    plt.show()

If the gradints are saved by a model this function can graph them over time

Adding an extra layer gave the model a greater space to be able to learn in and it was able to get a slighly better accuracy. The gain was an additional ~2% accuracy in the same number of epochs but it took ~30% longer to train. It's also worth noting that the accuracy increase was only in the resubstitution accuracy and not the validation accuracy which is a sign of overfitting. It also provides no benifits in situations where this model would be deployed.

In [ ]:
print_gradient_magnitudes(nn)

We can see that while the extra layer gave some extra accuracy, most of the learning was still done by the last layer.

The diminishing returns of adding layers is becoming more apparent. The extra layer is not adding much to the model and is slowing down training time. New layers past this point do not contribute at all to the model and are only slowing down training time.
